    <prj:ScienceGoal>
        <prj:name>Measuring the [CI] 1-0 line flux in TW Hya</prj:name>
        <prj:note>A measurement of the [CI] 1-0 line flux, or placing a strong upper limit on it, will allow to quantify the gas-phase carbon abundance in this protoplanetary disk. This will have a direct implication for the chemistry and thermal balance of any giant planets that form in this gas.

Previous work contains suggestions of a gas-phase carbon abundance in TW Hya that is lower than the standard cosmic or solar value. However, as it is based on CO isotopologs, these results must be backed up by atomic carbon measurements, which are free of the photodissociation and optical depth uncertainties that accompany CO isotopologs.

Our measurement will be the first robust determination of this quantity in the disk atmosphere. Because of optical depth effects, fluxes of CO and even 13CO are not very sensitive to the amount of available carbon. More optically thin isotopologs, e.g. C18O and C17O, may be subject to as yet poorly modelled isotope-specific photodissociation. Atomic carbon emission is very sensitive to the carbon abundance. Together with CO, O, C+ and HD, it allows to lift degeneracies between modeling parameters such as the gas to dust ratio, disk size and carbon abundance.</prj:note>
